ike-sounding) Jewish surnames.","Americanized form of German   Brucks  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Brucks","meanings":["North German:","probably a habitational name from Brucks (also Brux) which derives from Middle Low German <i>brōk</i> ‘low-lying marsh’.","reportedly also an altered form of Flemish (Dutch) <b>Broex</b>, an old variant of <b>Broeks</b> (see   Brooks  )."]},{"name":"Brook","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by a brook, stream, water-meadows or low, marshy ground, from Middle English <i>brook</i>, Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook, stream’; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, such as Brook (Kent, Rutland) or Brooke (Norfolk).","North German: topographic name for someone who lived by a water meadow or marsh, from Low German <i>brook</i> (cognate with German   Bruch   ‘swamp’ and Old English <i>brōc</i>; see 1 above).","Americanized form of Dutch <b>Broek</b>: topographic name from <i>broek</i>, a cognate of 2 above."]},{"name":"Brookes","meanings":["English (West Midlands): variant of   Brooks  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Nicholas Brooks was born about 1245, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Philip Brooks, was 32 and his mother, Mrs Philip Brooks, was 27. He married Anne Bushe about 1289, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He was buried in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1245–":"umbes 1245–Surnud","1245–Male":"1245–Surnud","1250–Female":"1250–Surnud","1290–Male":"1290–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1220–Female":"1220–Surnud","Abt 1240":"umbes 1240","1215":"1215","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1245":"1245","1220":"1220","about 1245":"umbes 1245","about 1289":"umbes 1289","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Chesterwaver, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of,,, England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",", Chesterwaver, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1245–":"noin 1245–Kuollut","1245–Male":"1245–Kuollut","1250–Female":"1250–Kuollut","1290–Male":"1290–Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1220–Female":"1220–Kuollut","Abt 1240":"noin 1240","1215":"1215","about 1290":"noin 1290","1245":"1245","1220":"1220","about 1245":"noin 1245","about 1289":"noin 1289","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","Chesterwaver, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of,,, England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",", Chesterwaver, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1245–":"environ 1245–Décédé"